Work progress being tracked [here](https://coda.io/d/Data-Science-and-ML-Eng_dK5h4iVEEUo/Reviewing-Process_sukDR#_lukij) and via #embeddings-for-churn-uplift-at-verizon Slack channel. We have delivered the required embeddings to Verizon using a mixture of features (Intent Patterns, Natural Audiences and VAE embeddings) to compose 120-vector sets for 3 consecutive rolling weeks.  Now pending Verizon validation.

# Overview

As we’re trying to meet the VZ ROI goal of $28M before renewal at the end of the year, we want to get more of our behavioural features in use for Verizon models and audiences. We’ve developed behavioural embeddings for predicting brand interest and there’s a big opportunity to deliver these to Verizon for their DS team to use in churn, upgrade and pricing models.

This would not only contribute to the ROI we generate for them, but also strengthen our relationship with a Verizon department that has historically been a detractor for us.

### Current state

We’ve understood from Verizon that they want to use our embedding features to predict:

- Churn;
- Upgrade opportunities;
- Pricing plan changes;

**As discussed with Jing from the VZ DS team, the highest priority (and their first validation tests) will be on churn, therefore we believe that should be our main focus in this initiative.** There is a risk for them to try the other models without letting us know once we deliver the embeddings. However, if we’re able to demonstrate viability for churn uplift, we believe that will provide sufficient value evidence for them to be open to further optimisation iterations for the other models.

For churn, they require us to deliver 3 sequential snapshots of embeddings in order to be able to run their tests. The weekly inference is driven by their goal to predict churners at a weekly cadence. Notably, they have plans to increase this frequency in the future.

Another constraint they pose is on the dimensionality of the vectors - they cannot process dimensions higher than 128 vectors requiring us to also maintain the schema of our historical churn features.

Luckily, as part of the ongoing churn efforts in ADS, we have a churn evaluation and validation process that can be used and upgraded as needed in development.

# Problem

### Target Audience

**Verizon Data Science team** uses some of our features for developing their own models which then impact campaign performance attributing ROI back to us. This team does not have access to weblogs which is why they use our insights as features instead (e.g. brands & interests). As we developed behavioural embeddings (VAEs currently used to model brands), they have asked to use these underlying signals as features for their models as described above.

### Problem overview

Our current embedding inference process is meant for a month’s worth of data and the latest optimised model produces embeddings at a higher dimensionality than Verizon can use with their existing models. Therefore, in addition to adapting our embeddings to meet the use case we will need to adapt our embeddings to account for these additional constraints.

Furthermore, as we are planning to validate the uplift potential of embeddings as part of this project, it is possible that the current model will not result in the desired outcome therefore requiring us to go through optimisation. In fact, because the model has been optimised for brand predictions, we consider churn to be a significantly different goal leading us to intuitively believe it’s very likely for optimisation work to be required in order to achieve the desired goal.

# Appetite

Allowing them to use these embeddings would increase our stickiness and partnership with a team that hasn’t historically been very supportive of us as a vendor for Verizon. Additionally, the more of our features they use for campaign targeting the more ROI we can claim ahead of renewal negotiations later this year.

### Goals & Success

We can demonstrate model performance uplift from using our embedding features in Verizon’s weekly churn prediction. Specifically, we need to be able to identify churners that Verizon wouldn’t have been able to identify before using these features.

Working back from our renewal date and factoring in the time it takes them to validate, we should deliver these by the end of August latest.

Definition of churn and requirements:

- Churners flagged as Voluntary in Verizon's churner feed within 7 Days from the date that churners are scored.
- Desired offset window between target window and the most recent data is zero days - but we have to think about the operational challenges and what is the minimum offset possible.
  - We have a 3-day lag on processing data so we don’t get the data until 3 days after it’s been produced and by the time required aggregations have been generated it will have been min. a week before we can run any inference on data. Inference takes a further few days.
- The churn scores are used for numerous inbound (customer calls in) and outbound (email, txt, digital) marketing. They are used to qualify users for different offers of varying value and are used to determine which offers people receive and when. 
- VZ update churn predictions weekly - we should make an assessment of how well we can deliver features to support their weekly batch scoring cadence.
- The embeddings should not be too highly dimensional. The steer was to not go much bigger than a 50-vector, definitely no higher than 128.

### Non-goals

- Implementing the process to deliver refreshed embeddings to them at a cadence - this will be planned depending on the outcomes of this validation project.
- VZ are moving in the future via their PZAI model towards realtime on-demand scoring. For this exercise we will not attempt realtime inference. This will be part of future discussions.

### Risks & Rabbit holes

- What do we do if we have low confidence that our embeddings will produce uplift for VZ given our patchy knowledge of the downstream use case and the lack of optimisation?
- What do we do if we discover our embeddings do not produce uplift?
  - If the validation results aren’t optimal we’ll have to further optimise the embedding model for the specific use-cases. To avoid hefty handover processes, we should have both DS & ADS collaborating on this work from the beginning so that there is enough knowledge in both teams to work together towards the shared goal of making our embeddings useful to Verizon.
  - It’s possible that optimisation work - if required - will not fit within the initial appetite for this initiative and could require more time to achieve the desired outcomes.
- It is plausible that the weblog signal that is most predictive of churn occurs in the week before the churn event. The VAE currently treats all signal as equal if it occurs in any of the preceding 13 weeks. We need to consider how this impacts the decisions we need to make around how we configure, train and infer these embeddings. We may need to get tactical here to achieve the value. Can we even turn these around quickly enough to improve signal for weekly churn before renewal?
- We could also do a proxy evaluation for pricing and upgrade takes, though this may not be as useful or impactful in the beginning.
- Why do they want 3 sequential sets?
  - Potentially to have training, validation and test sets.
  - Or they could be looking at the differences to see who has the biggest changes in behaviour.
- The cost of producing 3 different sets will definitely increase our AWS and Databricks costs.

# Solution

We will start by using the currently deployed VAE model to infer embeddings as needed for churn. To work around the weekly constraint we could:

- Try monthly embeddings manually inferred on a rolling month window every week - this could help us get to validation without having to update the inference process for weekly volumes of data at first.
- We already have a churn evaluation process that determines uplift ‘value’ as follows:
  - We have a baseline churn portfolio model that is trained using Verizon’s MVP (crm data) plus weekly churn centile scores which represent the outputs from Verizon’s own churn propensity models
  - We assume that our embeddings will only create additional value to Verizon if they are able to increase the proportion of actual voluntary churners in the top decile of propensity scores when compared to the baseline (Additive Lift)
  - Verizon’s 2022 study shows that the proportion of churners in their top decile is approximately 0.91% per week, which is approx a “top decile multiple” of 5.7x the full population churn rate of 0.16% Any additive lift by IHQ is calculated by the formula:  
  
[data:image/svg+xml;supportsDarkMode=1;base64,](data:image/svg+xml;supportsDarkMode=1;base64,)

An additive lift of 2% against the proxy baseline model is anticipated to equate to very approximately **$7m of attributable value to IHQ**. The objective is clear - maximise Additive Lift

- Update the inference process to only consider weekly data volumes if the above isn’t suitable.
- If none of these options show uplift in our validation process, we should move on to optimising the embeddings specific for the churn use-case.
- Ideally, we’d start running all 3 of these efforts in parallel rather than sequential to ensure minimal wait-times to move on to a subsequent options once something doesn’t work, especially considering current DS intuition indicates that general embeddings might not work to produce uplift for the use-cases.
- We could create a set of ‘standard’ embeddings, and one or more sets of ‘reduced time’ embeddings and use the existing evaluation tools to see how much they are able to uplift against our baseline VZ proxy. That will help us understand how important it may be to deliver something non-standard to VZ to achieve the value we are hoping for. 

More thoughts about potential solutions [here](https://coda.io/d/VZ-Embeddings_du_2df56TEX/VZ-Embeddings-and-Delivery_su_bG#_lu-BA).
